President Jacob Zuma has extended his “deepest condolences” to the families of those who died during the horrific collision between a passenger train and a truck near Kroonstad in the Free State on Thursday. He also wished a speedy recovery to the survivors of the collision. “We wish to express our deepest condolences to the families affected by this horrible incident. This is a painful start to the new year for the nation. It has caused great shock and distress. We appeal to all road users across the country to observe discipline‚ patience and be vigilant at all times as they travel back to their respective destinations over this holiday period. Such loss of life should be prevented by all road users by observing the rules of the road at all times‚” Zuma said. Minister of Justice and Correctional Services‚ Michael Masutha confirmed the death of eight correctional services officials in a car accident on Tuesday. “The department has learnt with shock and great sadness of the passing away of eight correctional services officials in a horrific motor vehicle collision on Tuesday morning‚” the… May 5, 2015 HAVING recently done a great deal of road tripping around the Eastern Cape to Coffee Bay and to the north coast of Natal and back, I can identify with the report about the loss to the Harper family of young, precious Bianca (deepest sympathy to you all) and very importantly,… October 15, 2015   The South African government has condemned a terrorist attack on a hospital in the Pakistan city of Quetta on Monday in which at least 70 people were killed and more than 100 injured. Conveying his condolences to the Pakistani President Mamnoon Hussain and his people‚ President Jacob Zuma stated… August 9, 2016